{
  "text": "Education A commonplace observation is that spouses tend to have similar cultural and socio-economic characteristics [CITATION_1] . Two mechanisms have been proposed to explain this outcome. The matching hypothesis states that people prefer partners who are similar, whilst the competition hypothesis postulates a preference for the highest possible amount of a certain trait. Thus, if both sides prefer to marry 'up' and are reluctant to marry 'down', the result is homogamy [CITATION_2] . Studies testing these hypotheses in a range of Western countries have found evidence for both, but for different traits: matching on cultural traits, but competition on economic traits [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
  "correct_citation": {
